## Description {#details}

This file provides interfaces used to build and manipulate a call graph, which is a very useful tool for interprocedural optimization.

Every function in a module is represented as a node in the call graph. The callgraph node keeps track of which functions are called by the function corresponding to the node.

A call graph may contain nodes where the function that they correspond to is null. These &#39;external&#39; nodes are used to represent control flow that is not represented (or analyzable) in the module. In particular, this analysis builds one external node such that:
<ul>
<li>All functions in the module without internal linkage will have edges from this external node, indicating that they could be called by functions outside of the module.</li>
<li>All functions whose address is used for something more than a direct call, for example being stored into a memory location will also have an edge from this external node. Since they may be called by an unknown caller later, they must be tracked as such.</li>
</ul>


There is a second external node added for calls that leave this module. Functions have a call edge to the external node iff:
<ul>
<li>The function is external, reflecting the fact that they could call anything without internal linkage or that has its address taken.</li>
<li>The function contains an indirect function call.</li>
</ul>


As an extension in the future, there may be multiple nodes with a null function. These will be used when we can prove (through pointer analysis) that an indirect call site can call only a specific set of functions.

Because of these properties, the CallGraph captures a conservative superset of all of the caller-callee relationships, which is useful for transformations.

<Link id="l00165" /><CodeLine lineNumber="165" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/callgraphnode"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/callgraphnode/#a605c6f0d2e13294856a1e35c47b1ea18">CallGraphNode</a> &#123;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00167" /><CodeLine lineNumber="167"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// A pair of the calling instruction (a call or invoke)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00168" /><CodeLine lineNumber="168"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// and the call graph node being called.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00169" /><CodeLine lineNumber="169"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Call graph node may have two types of call records which represent an edge</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00170" /><CodeLine lineNumber="170"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// in the call graph - reference or a call edge. Reference edges are not</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00171" /><CodeLine lineNumber="171"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// associated with any call instruction and are created with the first field</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00172" /><CodeLine lineNumber="172"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// set to &#96;None&#96;, while real call edges have instruction address in this</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00173" /><CodeLine lineNumber="173"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// field. Therefore, all real call edges are expected to have a value in the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00174" /><CodeLine lineNumber="174"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// first field and it is not supposed to be &#96;nullptr&#96;.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00175" /><CodeLine lineNumber="175"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Reference edges, for example, are used for connecting broker function</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00176" /><CodeLine lineNumber="176"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// caller to the callback function for callback call sites.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00177" /><CodeLine lineNumber="177" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/callgraphnode/#afe3782c535fa39673c4e160fcbdf1515"><Highlight kind="normal">  </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">using </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/callgraphnode/#afe3782c535fa39673c4e160fcbdf1515">CallRecord</a> = std::pair&lt;std::optional&lt;WeakTrackingVH&gt;, <a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/callgraphnode/#a605c6f0d2e13294856a1e35c47b1ea18">CallGraphNode</a> &#42;&gt;;</Highlight></CodeLine>
